This paper is about improving neural machine translation models by using compositional representations of morphologically rich input. The paper focuses on natural language processing (NLP) and machine learning (ML) techniques, which are typically covered in the arXiv category cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also proposes the use of bi-directional recurrent neural networks, which are a common technique in deep learning and neural networks, covered in the arXiv category cs.LG (Machine Learning). Additionally, the paper discusses the use of character n-grams, which are a common technique in text processing and information retrieval, covered in the arXiv category cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also mentions the use of low-resource settings, which is a common topic in the arXiv category cs.NE (Neural and Evolutionary Computing). Finally, the paper discusses the use of different morphological typologies, which is a topic that can be covered in the arXiv category cs.CV (Computer Vision) when dealing with visual recognition of different writing systems.
